  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:cdi",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "The CDI is the Brazilian overnight interbank rate — the rate at which banks lend to each other for one business day. It is the most important benchmark for Brazilian fixed income: published daily by B3 (formerly CETIP); annualized on BUS/252 basis: CDI_annual = (1 + CDI_daily)^252 - 1; most Brazilian corporate bonds, loans, and swaps are indexed to CDI; '100% CDI' means index_perc = 1.0 (docs/financialtools/theory_quantitative_finance.md §7.1).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "CDI",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:rates"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:di-futures",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "DI futures (DI1 contracts) are exchange-traded interest rate futures on B3. Each contract references the accumulated CDI over its lifetime: quoted as annual rates on a BUS/252 discrete-annual basis; contract value at maturity BRL 100,000; settlement financial (no physical delivery); maturities on the first business day of selected months. DI futures prices are the primary input for constructing the CDI curve (docs/financialtools/theory_quantitative_finance.md §7.2).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "DI futures",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:rates"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:ptax",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "The PTAX is the official BRL/USD exchange rate published by the Central Bank of Brazil (BCB). It is used for: settlement of FX derivatives (NDFs, FX forwards); cross-currency swap valuations; regulatory reporting of FX exposures. The dataset uses 'PTAX V' (PTAX Venda / sell side) (docs/financialtools/theory_quantitative_finance.md §7.5).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "PTAX",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:fx"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:cupom-cambial",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Cupom cambial is the USD-denominated BRL interest rate (curves.md). Builds the Cupom Cambial term structure from covered interest rate parity using the DI curve, FX fixings, and FRC quotes. Convention: ACT/360, linear (simple) compounding (src/treasuryutils/financialtools/builders/cupom_cambial.py module docstring).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "Cupom cambial",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:rates"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:casado",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "USD/BRL Casado (spot-future basis) — BRL per 1000 USD (src/treasuryutils/datatools/metadata/fx_derived.yaml), used in the formula spot = (first_future - casado) / 1000 (src/treasuryutils/financialtools/builders/fx.py, FxSpotBuilder docstring).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "Casado",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:fx"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:frc",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "FRC (Forward Rate Agreement de Cupom Cambial) from Market Data API (src/treasuryutils/datatools/metadata/frc_data.yaml). Long-end vertices (FRC maturities): FRC quotes are already cupom cambial rates (loaded as decimals) (src/treasuryutils/financialtools/builders/cupom_cambial.py).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "FRC",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:rates"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:sofr-conventions",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "CDI uses (1+r)^(1/252) exponential on business days. SOFR uses 1 + r * days/360 simple on calendar days (1 on weekdays, 3 over weekends, accounting for holidays) (src/treasuryutils/financialtools/builders/sofr.py, SofrAccumulatedBuilder docstring; comparison table in docs/financialtools/curves.md, 'CDI vs. SOFR: a quick comparison').",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "SOFR conventions",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:rates"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:business-day-calendar",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "A business day calendar defines which dates are valid trading/settlement days for a given market. Weekends and public holidays are non-workdays. Financial contracts settle on workdays, accrual periods count workdays (or calendar days), and coupon schedules skip holidays. Without a calendar, date arithmetic like 'T+2 settlement' or 'add 5 business days' would be ambiguous (docs/calendartools/README.md).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "Business-day calendar",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:calendars"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:bus-252",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Brazilian fixed-income markets use BUS/252: the year fraction is business days / 252, where 252 is the approximate number of workdays in a Brazilian year. Because BUS/252 counts only workdays, the result depends on the calendar — a month with a holiday in it accrues slightly less than the same month without one. This is the standard for CDI-indexed instruments, government bonds (NTN, LTN, LFT), and most local derivatives (docs/calendartools/day_count.md).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "BUS/252",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:conventions"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:flat-forward",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Between any two known data points (curve 'nodes'), the curve assumes that the instantaneous forward rate is constant. It is the standard convention in Brazilian fixed-income markets. By contrast, the SOFR curve uses linear interpolation on yields, which is the standard convention for USD money-market instruments (docs/financialtools/curves.md, 'Interpolation: flat-forward explained').",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "Flat-forward interpolation",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:conventions"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:pit-discipline",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Point-in-time (PIT) discipline prevents look-ahead bias by ensuring fundamental data is only visible as of the date it was publicly available. A fiscal quarter ends on period_end (e.g. 2024-09-30), but the company may not file with CVM until weeks later (filing_date). A model running on 2024-10-01 must not see this filing (docs/equitytools/data_layer.md §PIT discipline).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "PIT discipline",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:conventions"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:scd-2",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Temporal entities follow the SCD-2 (Slowly Changing Dimension Type 2) pattern. Each version carries valid_from, valid_to, version, and reason fields. Intervals are half-open: [valid_from, valid_to) — a version is active when valid_from <= as_of < valid_to. The current version has valid_to = None (docs/adr/0012-scd2-versioning-protocol.md).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "SCD-2",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:conventions"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
  {
    "entityType": "glossaryTerm",
    "entityUrn": "urn:li:glossaryTerm:corporate-action-adjustment",
    "changeType": "UPSERT",
    "aspectName": "glossaryTermInfo",
    "aspect": {
      "json": {
        "definition": "Corporate action types: SPLIT, REVERSE_SPLIT, DIVIDEND, BONUS_SHARES, RIGHTS_ISSUE. adj_factor is the cumulative corporate-action adjustment factor (1.0 = unadjusted); must be > 0 (docs/equitytools/schemas.md, qnt_corporate_actions / qnt_daily_bars).",
        "termSource": "INTERNAL",
        "name": "Corporate-action adjustment",
        "parentNode": "urn:li:glossaryNode:equity"
      }
    },
    "systemMetadata": { "lastObserved": 1783555200000, "runId": "treasury-prod-2026-07" }
  },
